Although many said there was no clear front-runner among the 115 cardinals, Ratzinger's sermon at the pre-conclave mass put him in the limelight for conservatives. On April 19th white smoke rising from the chapel roof at 5:15 p.m. stayed white. Ratzinger had been chosen after four ballots. His victory was cheered widely as an extension of the legacy of John Paul II, but questioned by more liberal elements concerned by a sharply divided church. There was hope in the new pope's explanation that he would be Benedict XVI after Benedict XV who gave himself to "peacemaking, reconciliation and harmony." 